The possibilities for the still widely used wine-red CrSn stains which are worthwhile to mention here are based on the calcination of calcium carbonate, tin oxide, quartz and (green) chromium oxide.

In former days one used to make first a calcium stannate out of calcium carbonate and tin oxide in the ratio 40 : 60. This mixture was wet-milled and calcined at 1150 °C. This calcination product was than wet-milled together with quartz, tin oxide and a chromate, dried and calcined at 1280 °C. This calcined product was wet milled to the right fineness, washed till all soluble chromate salts were removed and then dried.

