Today, only the dry process is utilized by dry mixing calcium carbonate, tin oxide, quartz and chromium oxide. For a better dispersion of the chromium oxide, a pre-mix is often made of chromium oxide and quartz with an intensive mixer. The dry mixed batch is than calcined and the pigment is than dry milled to the right fineness. Special materials acting as a catalyst can be added to achieve darker colours.

Lilac colour stains are composed out of tin oxide and a chromium compound, in most cases potassium dichromate $"K"_2"Cr"_2"O"_7$ now replaced by chromium oxide. Materials as cerium oxide, boric acid and lithium carbonate are added following the development of that particular stain.

